value.0: The gray-skinned dwarf glances up from the carcass as you approach. "Ye again, is it now, traveler? Come, we can talk while I work."

The gray-skinned man inspects the Elkenbeast's carcass, his hands brushing lightly against its side. His brow is furrowed in concern. "Do ye have the Resistance potion from Nimmermaer's yet, traveler?"
Scratching at his beard, he glances up from the Elkenbeast. "Well, I entrusted ye with the money and ye gave your word. Best ye live up to it."
The young dwarf glances over to the nearby shrine, his brows furrowed in concentration. "He be gone," he says, the color fading from his face. "Johann..."
Wiping the tears from his face, the herdkeeper casts a defeated glance in your direction. "An ill wind, stranger. It be an ill wind you bring to the Barrow Dwarves..."

The young dwarf glances over to the nearby shrine, his brows furrowed in concentration. His face slowly softens into a smile. "Aye, he seems at rest now. Maybe it wasn't an ill wind that brought you after all."
The dwarf holds the potion up to the light, examining its murky contents. "Many thanks, my friend. I'll will administer it to the herd later tonight and hope it serves them well."
The gray-skinned man inspects the Elkenbeast's carcass, his hands brushing lightly against its side. His brow is furrowed in concern. "Ye bring ill winds, traveler," he advises, not looking up.
The man nods. "Travel well, stranger."
The dwarf grins at you. "That be hard to say. The herd and I have just returned with the spring and I've spent all my time settling them in. Check with the blacksmith, Angmar. He'll have heard."

The man clearly takes pride in his work and warms to your question. "The Clan trusts me to tend to the Elkenherd," he says. "During the winters, I take them down into the valleys where they'll be sheltered."
"This village be all that's left of the Sons of Brogan. We may be few in number but we are proud of spirit and stout of heart. If ye wish to know more, ye should visit the Guild Hall."

"These animals are free spirits," explains the dwarf patiently. "Their forebears sacrificed themselves to feed and clothe the Clan in its time of need. For that, we must always treat them with respect."
"When the winters come, the herd feels the call of their ancestors. I go with them to seem them safely through their journey. Spring be on its way, though, so I have brought them home to pasture."

"Aye, the Stone, is it? Well ye won't find it here, I'm afraid. The Clan keeps it yonder at the Barrow Site. Ye should visit the Guild Exhibits if ye be that interested, though. They tell a fair enough tale of it."
"You might call them a museum of sorts. They be a record of Clan history that we keep to honor the paths walked by our ancestors. They be kept upstairs at the Guild Hall."

"If ye be interested in the past of this place, I suggest ye visit them. Brogan himself, the Clan's exile, the Cavanaugh Stone, the founding of the Barrow Site, the collapse of the mines. It all be there."
The dwarf brushes a stray wisp of hair from his face. "The Barrow Site? It be the big, open air temple at the south edge of town. I should head there tonight yet and pay my respects."
"This village be all that's left of the Sons of Brogan. We may be few in number but we are proud of spirit and stout of heart. If ye wish to know more, ye should visit the Guild Exhibits"
The man lifts his fingers to his prominent nose, taking in the scent of the Elkenbeast's coat. "I don't know... She was fine when we made it in to town last night. Now she be dead."

"Stranger yet, with every hour the carcass grows warmer rather than colder. Mayhaps it be some fell disease, though not one I've ever seen before." You catch a glimpse of fear lurking behind his eyes.
"Well, it never hurts to take precautions. Think ye could run to Old Man Nimmermaer's and pick up one of his Resistance potions while I stay with the herd? You can keep any change he gives you..."
He claps you on the shoulder. "That be all right, stranger. I'll get to it meself, I guess, once I figure out a bit more of what befell this poor one here."
He sizes you up. "I don't know the old man's latest prices but 50 guilders should be enough. As I said, ye can keep any change he offers. What say ye?"
The dwarf points a stout finger over the heavy fence. "Due west of the Barrow Site, by the old well. Don't bother knocking. He's been near deaf for years."
The man breaks into a smile, shaking his head. "A curmudgeon if ever there was one, and as crusty as they come. He's a veteran of the mine collapse and one of the last living to have seen it."
"Since that day, he's cultivated an interest in the dark arts. Spells and artifacts and the like. He be mostly harmless, though, and the village has come to rely on his craftings."

He grasps your hand in his and gives it a firm shake. "Thank you, friend. I'd hate to see the entire herd fall to this same fate. I don't know the old man's latest prices but 50 guilders should be enough."
The dwarf smiles. "It's too late to help this one, I'm afraid, but the potion ye bought from Old Man Nimmermaer should be of some help to the herd. There be nothing more we can do but wait."
The young dwarf glances over to the nearby shrine, his brows furrowed in concentration. "He be gone," he says, the color fading from his face. "Johann..."
Wiping the tears from his face, the herdkeeper casts a defeated glance in your direction. "An ill wind, stranger. It be an ill wind you bring to the Barrow Dwarves..."

The young dwarf glances over to the nearby shrine, his brows furrowed in concentration. His face slowly softens into a smile. "Aye, he seems at rest now. Maybe it wasn't an ill wind that brought you after all."

His rough hands continue to grace the dead beast. "I don't know, stranger. There's something wrong, is all. Like the raven that keeps flitting around the Elkentree or the way the village has gone so quiet."

"And like this Elkenbeast here: dead yet the corpse stays warm. Or the late snows or the way me brother's soul don't seem at rest no more. Ye tell me why ye bring ill winds, stranger... Ye tell me..."

"Aye, he died to a crag cat twelve years past. There had been drought and the cat was in its first year, scared and hungry... Sometimes the animals take back the lives they've given us. It be their right."

"All winter I tended the herd without him, returning here with spring. I lay on that patch of dirt there all summer, thinking of him. He felt close there, somehow, so I built that little shrine to remember him by."

The dwarf ponders your question for a long time before answering. "I would tell him that I still keep the herd and... and that the crag cat survived the winter and found a mate. She be very grateful to him."
"Just a patch of dirt, some stones I've gathered along the way, and the memories of me brother. Why, what do you see?"
The dwarf gives you a wry grin. "Of course ye do, friend. The world be what the world be. As soon as two good folk start seeing it differently... why, nothing but madness can lie down that path."

The dwarf gives you a wry grin. "Ha! Ye put too much stock in the Guild Council's exhibits, friend. There be people in this village who have seen such gaping wounds within the earth but it be ages past."
The dwarf gives you a wry grin. "Ye have a fanciful imagination, friend. Me brother would have liked ye. That shrine be a testament to his life, not to his death."
"A fair enough question, I suppose." The man finally looks up to take in your face. "Forgive me manners; I've had me hands full since I returned. I be Bernhardt, Herdkeeper for the Clan."
"Folk who come here often do." He returns his attention to the Elkenbeast before him but it's clear that he's still interested in what you have to say. You sense that he's hungry for conversation.
"This village be all that's left of the Sons of Brogan. We may be few in number but we are proud of spirit and stout of heart. If ye wish to know more, ye should visit the Guild Hall."

The man clearly takes pride in his work and warms to your question. "The Clan trusts me to tend to the Elkenherd," he says. "During the winters, I take them down into the valleys where they'll be sheltered."

"These animals are free spirits," explains the dwarf patiently. "Their forebears sacrificed themselves to feed and clothe the Clan in its time of need. For that, we must always treat them with respect."
"When the winters come, the herd feels the call of their ancestors. I go with them to seem them safely through their journey. Spring be on its way, though, so I have brought them home to pasture."
"Uh, not yet."
"No, not yet."
"How does your brother's soul rest now?"
"Yuh, here it be."
"Yes, here it is."
"Goodbye."
"There be strangers come here lately?"
"Any other travelers come through town lately?"
"Where you just return from?"
"Where did you just return from?"
"What be this Clan you talk 'bout?"
"What Clan are you referring to?"
"Why you not shelter herd here?"
"Can't you shelter the herd here?"
"Me look for Cavanaugh Stone."
"I'm looking for the Cavanaugh Stone."
"What these Guild Exhibits be?"
"What are these Guild Exhibits?"
"Where this Barrow Site be?"
"Where's this Barrow Site?"
"What Clan you talk 'bout?"
"What Clan are you referring to?"
"What happen to Elkenbeast?"
"What's wrong with that Elkenbeast?"
"There be some way me can help?"
"Is there any way I can help?"
"Sorry, me can't help right now."
"Sorry, I'm afraid I can't help."
"Uh, how much you give me?"
"How much will you give me?"
"Where me find this guy's place?"
"Where can I find his shop?"
"Who be this Nimmermaer guy?"
"Who is this Nimmermaer fellow?"
"Resistance potion from Nimmermaer? Yuh, okay."
"A Resistance potion from Nimmermaer? I'll do it."
"How does your brother's soul rest now?"
"Why me bring ill winds?"
"Why do I bring ill winds?"
"Brother's soul?"
"Your brother's soul?"
"What you tell your brother if you could?"
"What would you tell your brother if you could?"
"That be all you see there? That shrine?"
"That's all you see there is that shrine?"
"Huh? Oh, nothing. Me see same as you."
"Nothing. I see the same as you."
"Me see tunnel to underworld."
"I see a portal to the underworld."
"Me see big waving stream of dark energy."
"I see a writhing mass of dark energy."
"Who you be?"
"Who are you?"
"Okay, me have other questions."
"I still have a few more questions."
"What Clan you talk 'bout?"
"What Clan are you referring to?"
"Where you just return from?"
"Where did you just return from?"
"Uh... What be a herdkeeper?"
"What does a herdkeeper do?"
"Why you not shelter them here?"
"Can't you shelter them here?"
